Ahahaha what:

Meme-stock traders again piled into shares of GameStop Corp. and AMC Entert=
ainment Holdings Inc. in a revival of the retail-trading frenzy that had ro=
cked markets during the pandemic.
The video-game retailer jumped as much as 113% on Tuesday, while the beleag=
uered movie theater chain surged 129% =E2=80=94 triggering multiple halts i=
n the trading of both throughout the morning. GameStop has picked up about =
$12 billion in market value this month as its stock has soared, while AMC h=
as gained some $2 billion.
The latest rally erupted on Monday following the return to social media of =
Keith Gill, who drove the meme-stock mania of 2021 under the moniker =E2=80=
=9CRoaring Kitty.=E2=80=9D Gill shot to fame that year by rallying day trad=
ers on Reddit in an effort to squeeze GameStop short sellers.
On Tuesday morning, AMC announced it had completed a previously announced a=
t-the-market offering of shares, raising about $250 million in total as it =
sold 72.5 million shares for an average price of $3.45. AMC traded as high =
as $11.88 on Tuesday.

So we talked yesterday about the GameStop rally, which appears to have been=
 sparked by Gill rather cryptically returning to Twitter/X. Gill of course =
led GameStop=E2=80=99s January 2021 trip to the moon, and is closely associ=
ated with that company in particular. (There is a movie about it!) But I ne=
glected to mention that AMC =E2=80=94=C2=A0whose association with Gill is p=
retty much =E2=80=9CKeith Gill memed GameStop, and AMC was also a meme stoc=
k=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0rallied hard yesterday, apparently on pure meme-s=
tock sympathy.=C2=A0
But why did AMC rally today? Well, probably also meme-stock sympathy; GameS=
top is up again. But if I were an AMC investor, I suppose I would find it b=
