      Weiss
   =20
 =20

Any time a financial firm goes bankrupt, someone will trot out the old Hemi=
ngway line: =E2=80=9CHow did _____ go bankrupt? Two ways. Gradually, then s=
uddenly.=E2=80=9D
  [3]
=C2=A0Hemingway says it about a person, and personal bankruptcy doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to happen that way: People can go bankrupt suddenly and then grad=
ually (medical debt), or only gradually (overspending), or only suddenly (c=
asino). Even business bankruptcy sometimes involves a slow steady slide int=
o insolvency; we talked the other day about Bed Bath & Beyond=E2=80=99s mon=
ths of waiting on the doorstep of bankruptcy while it sold more stock. But=
=C2=A0financial=C2=A0firm bankruptcies=C2=A0are pretty much always graduall=
y-then-suddenly. You run a very leveraged balance sheet, you do some stuff =
that leaves you poorly positioned, you hold your breath, someone notices, t=
here is a race by all of your creditors to call in their debts and you coll=
apse over a weekend. The essence of a financial firm is relying on flighty =
leverage; the only way for it to end is suddenly.
But here is Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Hema Parmar on the bankruptcy of Weiss Mult=
i-Strategy Advisers, which, fine, yes, was gradual-then-sudden =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0George Weiss told his employees to sell everything one Thursday =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but was about as close as you=E2=80=99ll get to an =E2=80=9Conly g=
radual=E2=80=9D hedge fund failure:

Interviews with about two dozen people familiar with Weiss and court docume=
nts depict a collapse caused not by a disastrous trade, but rather years of=
 high spending that the firm failed to rein in even as assets fell and perf=
ormance faltered. George Weiss, 81, and Chief Investment Officer Jordi Viss=
er, 57, ran the $2.3 billion firm with the glitz of larger multistrategy ri=
vals, but without the discipline, the ruthlessness to cut losing traders or=
 the ability to push more costs onto investors, according to the people and=
 court filings. =E2=80=A6
While Weiss lost money in only three of its 46 years in business, it strugg=
led to manage costs. The firm =E2=80=94 which ran $4 billion at its 2021 pe=
ak =E2=80=94 had at least 110 employees, including well-compensated traders=
 and a packed back-office staff, working out of offices in Manhattan, Miami=
 and Connecticut.
Rent for the 20th and 21st floor of its Park Avenue location alone totaled =
almost $3 million a year, a bankruptcy filing shows.
The firm kept senior and veteran executives even after they posted declines=
 of tens of millions of dollars. Deputy Chief Investment Officer Mike Edwar=
ds lost more than $100 million between 2020 and 2023 and stopped trading as=
 a result, people said. Edwards didn=E2=80=99t provide a comment for this s=
tory.
But rather than fire the underperformers =E2=80=94 as multistrategy firms c=
ommonly do =E2=80=94 Visser and Weiss kept their longtime colleagues on the=
 payroll.

The point from Agustin Lebron in the previous section is that, if you run a=
 multistrategy hedge fund, the right price to charge your clients is somewh=
ere between =E2=80=9Call of your alpha=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Call of your re=
turns.=E2=80=9D If you overshoot that just slightly you end up bankrupt, bu=
t you paid a lot of people well along the way.

