   =20
 =20

I wrote yesterday about UBS Group AG=E2=80=99s plans to perhaps pay its inv=
estment bankers bonuses if they refer business to its wealth management bus=
iness. I suggested that investment bankers would be =E2=80=9Chideously emba=
rrassed=E2=80=9D to pitch wealth management to their clients, but that=E2=
=80=99s what the bosses want:
And so every big investment bank will from time to time announce an initiat=
ive that is like =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re going to tell our investment banker=
s that they should really mention our wealth management business to their c=
orporate-executive clients,=E2=80=9D and it really does tell the investment=
 bankers that, and the investment bankers are like =E2=80=9Cyes we are team=
 players and want to help our wealth management colleagues bring in more re=
venue,=E2=80=9D but they shudder a little as they say it, and do they actua=
lly go out and pitch the wealth management business? I don=E2=80=99t know, =
I=E2=80=99m not in the meetings.
I got a few good reader emails. One reader wrote:
A banker's reluctance to provide referrals to their wealth management colle=
agues may be caused by the increased relationship risk the referral brings,=
=C2=A0not necessarily their mercenary nature.=C2=A0I can easily=C2=A0imagin=
e the client conversation: =E2=80=9CNice job running the books on that bond=
 issue, oh, and thanks for=C2=A0the intro=C2=A0to your wealth management bu=
ddy. The money I gave him is trailing my overall portfolio by 120 bps. I'll=
 call you if I need your advice again.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 Banking relations=
hips are under enough competitive pressure as is. Why introduce a new varia=
ble, over which you have no control?
And, sure, though if you are the chief executive officer of a big bank and =
you=E2=80=99re pushing for more cross-selling, ideally=C2=A0you=C2=A0think =
that your wealth managers do a good job? Ideally you could=C2=A0persuade=C2=
=A0your investment bankers that their wealth management colleagues are actu=
ally competent? But, right, the investment bankers will be skeptical. Anoth=
er reader wrote:
I am in a bunch of these meetings, and I can affirm that they do go pitch t=
he business, occasionally, gingerly, usually in a walk-and-talk at a confer=
ence where the wealth manager was standing outside the door of the meeting =
room.
Yes this is exactly how I pictured it. =E2=80=9CSo, it=E2=80=99s been great=
 seeing you. Oh we also do wealth management. Okay bye!=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Cross-selling (2)
   =20
 =20

That said, the idea is not a bad one. Good investment bankers understand th=
at, while their client is the company, the path to a good client relationsh=
ip runs through befriending and helping out the company=E2=80=99s executive=
s. Sometimes this means helping them out with good corporate-finance ideas =
that will impress the board or their bosses,=C2=A0but other times it means =
helping them out in their personal capacity. Classically this means taking =
them golfing. Sometimes it means referring executives to new jobs, which ca=
n be good for the new employer and also make the executive more loyal to th=
e banker. And sometimes hooking an executive up with a really good private =
wealth adviser =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you happen to have one =E2=80=94=C2=A0is=
=C2=A0good client service. The question is just how confident the investmen=
t bankers are that their bank=E2=80=99s private wealth managers are really =
good ones.
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Heather Perlberg caught up a while back with Don Engel,=
 a former Drexel Burnham Lambert investment banker who died earlier this ye=
ar. He seems to have specialized in winning corporate financing business by=
 helping executives in their personal capacity:

Engel was quick to admit that he was never one of the financial brains at D=
rexel. He worked in the corporate finance department but he didn=E2=80=99t =
have an MBA. What he did have, however, was an almost preternatural sense f=
or what clients really wanted. That sense, Engel insisted, could be at time=
s more useful than numbers and business school case studies ever could. CEO=
s have lonely jobs, he told me. So, he set out to become a kind of therapis=
t-in-residence at Drexel =E2=80=94 the guy CEOs and corporate raiders could=
 turn to in confidence to talk through personal problems. Marriages and aff=
airs, current or prospective, were usually at the top of the list. =E2=80=
=A6
=E2=80=9CIn most cases, the CEO has no one to talk to,=E2=80=9D Engel said.=
 =E2=80=9CHe can=E2=80=99t tell people what=E2=80=99s going on with his wif=
e, with his girlfriend. He can=E2=80=99t tell them about what=E2=80=99s goi=
ng on with his mistress.=E2=80=99=E2=80=99
He went on: =E2=80=9CHe is imploding, and there I am, because I understand =
all this. So then, once you start to understand that person, then you have =
a relationship. And that=E2=80=99s what I did best.=E2=80=9D

If your investment banking job consists of talking to CEOs about their mist=
resses, might you also get into the ancillary business of referring potenti=
al mistresses to the executives? Engel absolutely did, is the point of the =
rest of the article.

