e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked the other day</a> about Bed B=
ath &amp; Beyond=E2=80=99s months of waiting on the doorstep of bankruptcy =
while it sold more stock. But=C2=A0<em>financial=C2=A0</em>firm bankruptcie=
s=C2=A0are pretty much always gradually-then-suddenly. You run a very lever=
aged balance sheet, you do some stuff that leaves you poorly positioned, yo=
u hold your breath, someone notices, there is a race by all of your credito=
rs to call in their debts and you collapse over a weekend. The essence of a=
 financial firm is relying on flighty leverage; the only way for it to end =
is suddenly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Hema Parmar on=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35377662.286337/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMTQvaG93LWEt=
NDYteWVhci1vbGQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZC13ZW50LWJhbmtydXB0LXdpdGhvdXQtYS1ibG93dXA_Y21=
