 on election outcomes, you have to go to the CFTC for approval. Exchanges=
=C2=A0occasionally do ask the CFTC for approval to list election contracts,=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> and then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3537=
7662.286337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODc=
4MC0yMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdda383ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the CFTC says no</a>.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it could theoretically say yes. And then t=
here=E2=80=99d be an election, and one candidate would win, and the other c=
andidate would say =E2=80=9Cno this election was stolen from me,=E2=80=9D a=
nd the outcome for the financial purpose of settling the contracts would be=
 disputed. And either the losing candidate would be=C2=A0<em>wrong</em>, an=
d lying about the election being stolen, in which case there would be argua=
ble commodities fraud inflating the price of his contracts. Or he=E2=80=99d=
 be=C2=A0<em>right=C2=A0</em>about the election being stolen, in which case=
 there would be arguable commodities fraud depressing the price of his cont=
racts. And people with money on the line would go to court. And the thesis =
of =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D is that US law is someh=
ow more=C2=A0<em>responsive=C2=A0</em>to financial-market claims than it is=
 to other, substantive claims, and so the courts and the CFTC would feel mo=
re compelled to address the claim =E2=80=9Cthis election was stolen, which =
is commodities fraud,=E2=80=9D than they would to address the claim =E2=80=
=9Cthis election was stolen, which is bad on its own.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I realize that all of this sounds incredibly d=
umb and far-fetched, but in my defense last week the CFTC <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35377662.286337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z=
0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODkwNy0yNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB1ce54150" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">proposed new rules to ban election contracts</a>. This =
is=C2=A0in part, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
5377662.286337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXN0cmFsY29kZXh0ZW4uY29tL3AvbWFudGljLW1vbmRh=
eS01MTMyNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB64eed999" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">as Scott Alexander po=
ints out</a>, so it can save time<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[5]</span>
</a>: Right now, people ask the CFTC to approve election contracts, and it =
says no; if it=E2=80=99s always going to say no, it=E2=80=99s simpler to ha=
ve a blanket rule against the contracts so people stop asking. But it is al=
so in part because the CFTC does not want to meddle in elections. Here is t=
he <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35377662.286337=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1NwZWVjaGVzVGVzdGltb255L2JlaG5hbX=
N0YXRlbWVudDA1MTAyNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb7d8a53f" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">statement o=
f CFTC Chairman Rostin Behnam</a> proposing the rules:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be clear, that means that event contracts o=
n the outcome of a political contest such as an election could not be liste=
d for trading or accepted for clearing under the proposed rule. Such contra=
cts not only fail to serve the economic purpose of the futures markets=E2=
=80=94they are illegal in several states and could potentially and impermis=
sibly preempt State responsibilities for overseeing federal elections. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Allowing these contracts would push the CFTC, =
a financial market regulator, into a position far beyond its Congressional =
mandate and expertise. To be blunt, such contracts would put the CFTC in th=
e role of an election cop.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CFTC=E2=80=99s jurisdiction as mandated by=
 Congress and solidified in our statute, the Commodity Exchange Act, recogn=
izes our expertise in markets for goods, services, rights, and interests=E2=
=80=94which can include events associated with financial, commercial, or ec=
onomic consequences. We are tasked with upholding the public interest by en=
suring that America=E2=80=99s derivatives markets provide a means for manag=
ing and assuming price risks and providing for price discovery through liqu=
id, fair, open, transparent, and financially secure trading facilities. Mar=
ket integrity is featured so prominently within that mandate that the CFTC =
has civil enforcement authority when it comes to the potential for fraud, m=
anipulation, and other abuses such as the dissemination of false informatio=
n in the underlying or commodity cash markets. Political control contracts =
on CFTC-regulated exchanges would push the CFTC far beyond this historical =
expertise and jurisdiction, and potentially place the CFTC in the position =
of monitoring such markets for fraud and manipulation in elections themselv=
es.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/35377662.286337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3J=
lZ3VsYXRpb24vY2Z0Yy13YW50cy10by1iYW4tdHJhZGVzLXRpZWQtdG8tZWxlY3Rpb25zLXNwb3=
J0cy1hbmQtYXdhcmRzLWNvbnRlc3RzLTNkNmZiM2M2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2d6b141=
8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">also looking to ban</a> contracts relating to awards shows, an=
d that strikes me as a mistake. I can see how it would be=C2=A0bad, for the=
 CFTC and for democratic legitimacy, for the CFTC to get into the business =
of policing elections. But surely it would=C2=A0just be fun for the CFTC to=
 police the Oscars?</p>
