<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, the idea is not a bad one. Good inv=
estment bankers understand that, while their client is the <em>company</em>=
, the path to a good client relationship runs through befriending and helpi=
ng out the company=E2=80=99s <em>executives</em>. Sometimes this means help=
ing them out with good corporate-finance ideas that will impress the board =
or their bosses,=C2=A0but other times it means helping them out in their pe=
rsonal capacity. Classically this means taking them golfing. Sometimes it m=
eans referring executives to new jobs, which can be good for the new employ=
er and also make the executive more loyal to the banker. And sometimes hook=
ing an executive up with a really good private wealth adviser =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if you happen to have one =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>good client se=
rvice. The question is just how confident the investment bankers are that t=
heir bank=E2=80=99s private wealth managers are really good ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Heather Perlberg <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35377662.286337/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMTQvZHJleGVsLXMtZG9u=
LWVuZ2VsLWhhcy1kaWVkLWhpcy10YWxlcy1vZi13YWxsLXN0cmVldC13b21lbi1hbmQtd2VhbHR=
oLWxpdmUtb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxNDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG=
1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0d=
WZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaca7c2ea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">caught up a while back</a> w=
ith Don Engel, a former Drexel Burnham Lambert investment banker who died e=
arlier this year. He seems to have specialized in winning corporate financi=
ng business by helping executives in their personal capacity:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Engel was quick to admit that he was never one=
 of the financial brains at Drexel. He worked in the corporate finance depa=
rtment but he didn=E2=80=99t have an MBA. What he did have, however, was an=
 almost preternatural sense for what clients really wanted. That sense, Eng=
el insisted, could be at times more useful than numbers and business school=
 case studies ever could. CEOs have lonely jobs, he told me. So, he set out=
 to become a kind of therapist-in-residence at Drexel =E2=80=94 the guy CEO=
s and corporate raiders could turn to in confidence to talk through persona=
l problems. Marriages and affairs, current or prospective, were usually at =
the top of the list. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn most cases, the CEO has no one to =
talk to,=E2=80=9D Engel said. =E2=80=9CHe can=E2=80=99t tell people what=E2=
=80=99s going on with his wife, with his girlfriend. He can=E2=80=99t tell =
them about what=E2=80=99s going on with his mistress.=E2=80=99=E2=80=99</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He went on: =E2=80=9CHe is imploding, and ther=
e I am, because I understand all this. So then, once you start to understan=
d that person, then you have a relationship. And that=E2=80=99s what I did =
best.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If your investment banking job consists of tal=
king to CEOs about their mistresses, might you also get into the ancillary =
business of referring potential mistresses to the executives? Engel absolut=
ely did, is the point of the rest of the article.</p>
